@node How to run a site with GNU Artanis
@section How to run a site with GNU Artanis

This is the simplest case to run a site:
@example
#!/bin/env guile
!#
(use-modules (artanis artanis))
(init-server)
(get "/hello" (lambda () "hello world"))
(run)
@end example

@node Initialization
@section Initialization

It's better to use (init-server) to init GNU Artanis.
@example
(init-server #:statics '(png jpg jpeg ico html js css)
             #:cache-statics? #f #:exclude '())
@end example

@verb{~#:statics~} specifies the static files with the extension file. GNU Artanis is based on URL remapping, so this keyword let you avoid to handle each static file types. In default, it covers the most static file types. So you may ignore it usually.

@verb{~#:cache-statics?~} indicates if the static files should be cached.

@verb{~#:exclude~} specifies the types should be excluded. This is useful when you want to generate image files dynamically. Even JavaScript/CSS could be generated dynamically, depends your design.

